Reasoning: I inspected the workbook and found one sheet, `Sheet1`, with transaction data in rows 2–3 and summary areas below. Cell `A26` contains the text month name `"January"`, not a date, so the existing formula in `B26` is incorrect for two reasons:

1. It sums column `K`, but the instruction says the sum should come from column `I`.
2. It compares dates in column `C` to `A26`, but `A26` is just a month name text value.

To follow the instruction literally, I should update `B26` so it sums values in column `I` only where the month of the corresponding date in column `C` matches the month name in `A26`.

A safe LibreOffice-compatible approach is to use `SUMPRODUCT` with `MONTH()` and `MATCH()` against an inline month-name list. I’ll bound the range to the actual data rows (2:3), save the workbook to the output directory with the same filename, recalculate, and verify the resulting cached value in `B26`.
Code:
```repl
import os, shutil
from openpyxl import load_workbook

input_path = input_spreadsheet
filename = os.path.basename(input_path)
output_path = os.path.join("/sandbox/output/output_spreadsheet", filename)

# Load workbook and modify B26
wb = load_workbook(input_path)
ws = wb["Sheet1"]

# Correct formula: sum Column I where month of Column C matches month name in A26
ws["B26"] = '=SUMPRODUCT((MONTH(C2:C3)=MATCH(A26,{"January","February","March","April","May","June","July","August","September","October","November","December"},0))*I2:I3)'

wb.save(output_path)
print("Saved:", output_path)
print("Formula written to B26:", ws["B26"].value)

# Recalculate and verify
recalc_result = await recalculate(output_path)
print("Recalc:", recalc_result)

wb_check_formula = load_workbook(output_path, data_only=False)
wb_check_values = load_workbook(output_path, data_only=True)
wsf = wb_check_formula["Sheet1"]
wsv = wb_check_values["Sheet1"]

print("Verified formula B26:", wsf["B26"].value)
print("Verified cached value B26:", wsv["B26"].value)

output_spreadsheet = output_path
```
